(see E2E Tests section)\\n    21→\\n    22→## Tech Stack\\n    23→\\n    24→- Language: Go 1.25.x\\n    25→- Build tool: mise, go modules\\n    26→- Linting: golangci-lint\\n    27→\\n    28→## Development\\n    29→\\n    30→### Running Tests\\n    31→```bash\\n    32→mise run test\\n    33→```\\n    34→\\n    35→### Running Integration Tests\\n    36→```bash\\n    37→mise run test:integration\\n    38→```\\n    39→\\n    40→### Running All Tests (CI)\\n    41→```bash\\n    42→mise run test:ci\\n    43→```\\n    44→\\n    45→Integration tests use the `//go:build integration` build tag and are located in `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/`.\\n    46→\\n    47→### Running E2E Tests (Only When Explicitly Requested)\\n    48→\\n    49→**IMPORTANT: Do NOT run E2E tests proactively.** E2E tests make real API calls through AI agents, which consume tokens and cost money. Only run them when the user explicitly asks for E2E testing.\\n    50→\\n    51→```bash\\n    52→# Requires Claude Code to be installed and authenticated\\n    53→E2E_AGENT=claude-code go test -tags=e2e ./cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/...\\n    54→\\n    55→# Run a specific test\\n    56→E2E_AGENT=claude-code go test -tags=e2e -run TestE2E_BasicWorkflow ./cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/...\\n    57→```\\n    58→\\n    59→E2E tests:\\n    60→- Use the `//go:build e2e` build tag\\n    61→- Located in `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/`\\n    62→- Test real agent interactions (Claude Code creating files, committing, etc.)\\n    63→- Validate checkpoint scenarios documented in `docs/architecture/checkpoint-scenarios.md`\\n    64→- Support multiple agents via `E2E_AGENT` env var (`claude-code`, `gemini`, `opencode`)\\n    65→\\n    66→**Environment variables:**\\n    67→- `E2E_AGENT` - Agent to test with (default: `claude-code`)\\n    68→- `E2E_CLAUDE_MODEL` - Claude model to use (default: `haiku` for cost efficiency)\\n    69→- `E2E_TIMEOUT` - Timeout per prompt (default: `2m`)\\n    70→\\n    71→### Test Parallelization\\n    72→\\n    73→**Always use `t.Parallel()` in tests.** Every top-level test function and subtest should call `t.Parallel()` unless it modifies process-global state (e.g., `os.Chdir()`).\\n    74→\\n    75→```go\\n    76→func TestFeature_Foo(t *testing.T) {\\n    77→    t.Parallel()\\n    78→    // ...\\n    79→}\\n    80→\\n    81→// Integration tests: RunForAllStrategies handles t.Parallel() for subtests internally,\\n    82→// but the top-level test still needs it\\n    83→func TestFeature_Bar(t *testing.T) {\\n    84→    t.Parallel()\\n    85→    RunForAllStrategies(t, func(t *testing.T, env *TestEnv, strategyName string) {\\n    86→        // ...\\n    87→    })\\n    88→}\\n    89→```\\n    90→\\n    91→**Exception:** Tests that modify process-global state cannot be parallelized. This includes `os.Chdir()`/`t.Chdir()` and `os.Setenv()`/`t.Setenv()` — Go's test framework will panic if these are used after `t.Parallel()`.\\n    92→\\n    93→### Linting and Formatting\\n    94→```bash\\n    95→mise run fmt && mise run lint\\n    96→```\\n    97→\\n    98→### Before Every Commit (REQUIRED)\\n    99→\\n   100→**CI will fail if you skip these steps:**\\n   101→\\n   102→```bash\\n   103→mise run fmt      # Format code (CI enforces gofmt)\\n   104→mise run lint     # Lint check (CI enforces golangci-lint)\\n   105→mise run test:ci  # Run all tests (unit + integration)\\n   106→```\\n   107→\\n   108→Or combined: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test:ci`\\n   109→\\n   110→**Common CI failures from skipping this:**\\n   111→- `gofmt` formatting differences → run `mise run fmt`\\n   112→- Lint errors → run `mise run lint` and fix issues\\n   113→- Test failures → run `mise run test` and fix\\n   114→\\n   115→### Code Duplication Prevention\\n   116→\\n   117→Before implementing Go code, use `/go:discover-related` to find existing utilities and patterns that might be reusable.\\n   118→\\n   119→**Check for duplication:**\\n   120→```bash\\n   121→mise run dup           # Comprehensive check (threshold 50) with summary\\n   122→mise run dup:staged    # Check only staged files\\n   123→mise run lint          # Normal lint includes dupl at threshold 75 (new issues only)\\n   124→mise run lint:full     # All issues at threshold 75\\n   125→```\\n   126→\\n   127→**Tiered thresholds:**\\n   128→- **75 tokens** (lint/CI) - Blocks on serious duplication (~20+ lines)\\n   129→- **50 tokens** (dup) - Advisory, catches smaller patterns (~10+ lines)\\n   130→\\n   131→When duplication is found:\\n   132→1. Check if a helper already exists in `common.go` or nearby utility files\\n   133→2. If not, consider extracting the duplicated logic to a shared helper\\n   134→3. If duplication is intentional (e.g., test setup), add a `//nolint:dupl` comment with explanation\\n   135→\\n   136→## Code Patterns\\n   137→\\n   138→### Error Handling\\n   139→\\n   140→The CLI uses a specific pattern for error output to avoid duplication between Cobra and main.go.\\n   141→\\n   142→**How it works:**\\n   143→- `root.go` sets `SilenceErrors: true` globally - Cobra never prints errors\\n   144→- `main.go` prints errors to stderr, unless the error is a `SilentError`\\n   145→- Commands return `NewSilentError(err)` when they've already printed a custom message\\n   146→\\n   147→**When to use `SilentError`:**\\n   148→Use `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message instead of the raw error:\\n   149→\\n   150→```go\\n   151→// In a command's RunE function:\\n   152→if _, err := paths.RepoRoot(); err != nil {\\n   153→    cmd.SilenceUsage = true  // Don't show usage for prerequisite errors\\n   154→    fmt.Fprintln(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"Not a git repository. Please run 'entire enable' from within a git repository.\\\")\\n   155→    return NewSilentError(errors.New(\\\"not a git repository\\\"))\\n   156→}\\n   157→```\\n   158→\\n   159→**When NOT to use `SilentError`:**\\n   160→For normal errors where the default error message is sufficient, just return the error directly. main.go will print it:\\n   161→\\n   162→```go\\n   163→// Normal error - main.go will print \\\"unknown strategy: foo\\\"\\n   164→return fmt.Errorf(\\\"unknown strategy: %s\\\", name)\\n   165→```\\n   166→\\n   167→**Key files:**\\n   168→- `errors.go` - Defines `SilentError` type and `NewSilentError()` constructor\\n   169→- `root.go` - Sets `SilenceErrors: true` on root command\\n   170→- `main.go` - Checks for `SilentError` before printing\\n   171→\\n   172→### Settings\\n   173→\\n   174→All settings access should go through the `settings` package (`cmd/entire/cli/settings/`).\\n   175→\\n   176→**Why a separate package:**\\n   177→The `settings` package exists to avoid import cycles. The `cli` package imports `strategy`, so `strategy` cannot import `cli`. The `settings` package provides shared settings loading that both can use.\\n   178→\\n   179→**Usage:**\\n   180→```go\\n   181→import \\\"github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/settings\\\"\\n   182→\\n   183→// Load full settings object\\n   184→s, err := settings.Load()\\n   185→if err != nil {\\n   186→    // handle error\\n   187→}\\n   188→if s.Enabled {\\n   189→    // ...\\n   190→}\\n   191→\\n   192→// Or use convenience functions\\n   193→if settings.IsSummarizeEnabled() {\\n   194→    // ...\\n   195→}\\n   196→```\\n   197→\\n   198→**Do NOT:**\\n   199→- Read `.entire/settings.json` or `.entire/settings.local.json` directly with `os.ReadFile`\\n   200→- Duplicate settings parsing logic in other packages\\n   201→- Create new settings helpers without adding them to the `settings` package\\n   202→\\n   203→**Key files:**\\n   204→- `settings/settings.go` - `EntireSettings` struct, `Load()`, and helper methods\\n   205→- `config.go` - Higher-level config functions that use settings (for `cli` package consumers)\\n   206→\\n   207→### Logging vs User Output\\n   208→\\n   209→- **Internal/debug logging**: Use `logging.Debug/Info/Warn/Error(ctx, msg, attrs...)` from `cmd/entire/cli/logging/`. Writes to `.entire/logs/`.\\n   210→- **User-facing output**: Use `fmt.Fprint*(cmd.OutOrStdout(), ...)` or `cmd.ErrOrStderr()`.\\n   211→\\n   212→Don't use `fmt.Print*` for operational messages (checkpoint saves, hook invocations, strategy decisions) - those should use the `logging` package.\\n   213→\\n   214→**Privacy**: Don't log user content (prompts, file contents, commit messages). Log only operational metadata (IDs, counts, paths, durations).\\n   215→\\n   216→### Git Operations\\n   217→\\n   218→We use github.com/go-git/go-git for most git operations, but with important exceptions:\\n   219→\\n   220→#### go-git v5 Bugs - Use CLI Instead\\n   221→\\n   222→**Do NOT use go-git v5 for `checkout` or `reset --hard` operations.**\\n   223→\\n   224→go-git v5 has a bug where `worktree.Reset()` with `git.HardReset` and `worktree.Checkout()` incorrectly delete untracked directories even when they're listed in `.gitignore`. This would destroy `.entire/` and `.worktrees/` directories.\\n   225→\\n   226→Use the git CLI instead:\\n   227→```go\\n   228→// WRONG - go-git deletes ignored directories\\n   229→worktree.Reset(&git.ResetOptions{\\n   230→    Commit: hash,\\n   231→    Mode:   git.HardReset,\\n   232→})\\n   233→\\n   234→// CORRECT - use git CLI\\n   235→cmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"reset\\\", \\\"--hard\\\", hash.String())\\n   236→```\\n   237→\\n   238→See `HardResetWithProtection()` in `common.go` and `CheckoutBranch()` in `git_operations.go` for examples.\\n   239→\\n   240→Regression tests in `hard_reset_test.go` verify this behavior - if go-git v6 fixes this issue, those tests can be used to validate switching back.\\n   241→\\n   242→#### Repo Root vs Current Working Directory\\n   243→\\n   244→**Always use repo root (not `os.Getwd()`) when working with git-relative paths.**\\n   245→\\n   246→Git commands like `git status` and `worktree.Status()` return paths relative to the **repository root**, not the current working directory. When Claude runs from a subdirectory (e.g., `/repo/frontend`), using `os.Getwd()` to construct absolute paths will produce incorrect results for files in sibling directories.\\n   247→\\n   248→```go\\n   249→// WRONG - breaks when running from subdirectory\\n   250→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // e.g., /repo/frontend\\n   251→absPath := filepath.Join(cwd, file)  // file=\\\"api/src/types.ts\\\" → /repo/frontend/api/src/types.ts (WRONG)\\n   252→\\n   253→// CORRECT - use repo root\\n   254→repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()  // or strategy.GetWorktreePath()\\n   255→absPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, file)  // → /repo/api/src/types.ts (CORRECT)\\n   256→```\\n   257→\\n   258→This also affects path filtering. The `paths.ToRelativePath()` function rejects paths starting with `..`, so computing relative paths from cwd instead of repo root will filter out files in sibling directories:\\n   259→\\n   260→```go\\n   261→// WRONG - filters out sibling directory files\\n   262→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // /repo/frontend\\n   263→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", cwd)  // returns \\\"\\\" (filtered out as \\\"../api/file.ts\\\")\\n   264→\\n   265→// CORRECT - keeps all repo files\\n   266→repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()\\n   267→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", repoRoot)  // returns \\\"api/file.ts\\\"\\n   268→```\\n   269→\\n   270→**When to use `os.Getwd()`:** Only when you actually need the current directory (e.g., finding agent session directories that are cwd-relative).\\n   271→\\n   272→**When to use repo root:** Any time you're working with paths from git status, git diff, or any git-relative file list.\\n   273→\\n   274→Test case in `state_test.go`: `TestFilterAndNormalizePaths_SiblingDirectories` documents this bug pattern.\\n   275→\\n   276→### Session Strategies (`cmd/entire/cli/strategy/`)\\n   277→\\n   278→The CLI uses a strategy pattern for managing session data and checkpoints. Each strategy implements the `Strategy` interface defined in `strategy.go`.\\n   279→\\n   280→#### Core Interface\\n   281→All strategies implement:\\n   282→- `SaveStep()` - Save session step checkpoint (code + metadata)\\n   283→- `SaveTaskStep()` - Save subagent task step checkpoint\\n   284→- `GetRewindPoints()` / `Rewind()` - List and restore to checkpoints\\n   285→- `GetSessionLog()` / `GetSessionInfo()` - Retrieve session data\\n   286→- `ListSessions()` / `GetSession()` - Session discovery\\n   287→\\n   288→#### Available Strategies\\n   289→\\n   290→| Strategy | Main Branch | Metadata Storage | Use Case |\\n   291→|----------|-------------|------------------|----------|\\n   292→| **manual-commit** (default) | Unchanged (no commits) | `entire/<HEAD-hash>-<worktreeHash>` branches + `entire/checkpoints/v1` | Recommended for most workflows |\\n   293→| **auto-commit** | Creates clean commits | Orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch | Teams that want code commits from sessions |\\n   294→\\n   295→#### Strategy Details\\n   296→\\n   297→**Manual-Commit Strategy** (`manual_commit*.go`) - Default\\n   298→- **Does not modify** the active branch - no commits created on the working branch\\n   299→- Creates shadow branch `entire/<HEAD-commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>` per base commit + worktree\\n   300→- **Worktree-specific branches** - each git worktree gets its own shadow branch namespace, preventing conflicts\\n   301→- **Supports multiple concurrent sessions** - checkpoints from different sessions in the same directory interleave on the same shadow branch\\n   302→- Session logs are condensed to permanent `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch on user commits\\n   303→- Builds git trees in-memory using go-git plumbing APIs\\n   304→- Rewind restores files from shadow branch commit tree (does not use `git reset`)\\n   305→- **Location-independent transcript resolution** - transcript paths are always computed dynamically from the current repo location (via `agent.GetSessionDir` + `agent.ResolveSessionFile`), never stored in checkpoint metadata. This ensures restore/rewind works after repo relocation or across machines.\\n   306→- Tracks session state in `.git/entire-sessions/` (shared across worktrees)\\n   307→- **Shadow branch migration** - if user does stash/pull/rebase (HEAD changes without commit), shadow branch is automatically moved to new base commit\\n   308→- **Orphaned branch cleanup** - if a shadow branch exists without a corresponding session state file, it is automatically reset when a new session starts\\n   309→- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n   310→- `AllowsMainBranch() = true` - safe to use on main/master since it never modifies commit history\\n   311→\\n   312→**Auto-Commit Strategy** (`auto_commit.go`)\\n   313→- Code commits to active branch with **clean history** (commits have `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer only)\\n   314→- Metadata stored on orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch at sharded paths: `<id[:2]>/<id[2:]>/`\\n   315→- Uses `checkpoint.WriteCommitted()` for metadata storage\\n   316→- Checkpoint ID (12-hex-char) links code commits to metadata on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   317→- Full rewind allowed if commit is only on current branch (not in main); otherwise logs-only\\n   318→- Rewind via `git reset --hard`\\n   319→- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n   320→- `AllowsMainBranch() = true` - creates commits on active branch, safe to use on main/master\\n   321→\\n   322→#### Key Files\\n   323→\\n   324→- `strategy.go` - Interface definition and context structs (`StepContext`, `TaskStepContext`, `RewindPoint`, etc.)\\n   325→- `registry.go` - Strategy registration/discovery (factory pattern with `Get()`, `List()`, `Default()`)\\n   326→- `common.go` - Shared helpers for metadata extraction, tree building, rewind validation, `ListCheckpoints()`\\n   327→- `session.go` - Session/checkpoint data structures\\n   328→- `push_common.go` - Shared PrePush logic for pushing `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch\\n   329→- `manual_commit.go` - Manual-commit strategy main implementation\\n   330→- `manual_commit_types.go` - Type definitions: `SessionState`, `CheckpointInfo`, `CondenseResult`\\n   331→- `manual_commit_session.go` - Session state management (load/save/list session states)\\n   332→- `manual_commit_condensation.go` - Condense logic for copying logs to `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   333→- `manual_commit_rewind.go` - Rewind implementation: file restoration from checkpoint trees\\n   334→- `manual_commit_git.go` - Git operations: checkpoint commits, tree building\\n   335→- `manual_commit_logs.go` - Session log retrieval and session listing\\n   336→- `manual_commit_hooks.go` - Git hook handlers (prepare-commit-msg, post-commit, pre-push)\\n   337→- `manual_commit_reset.go` - Shadow branch reset/cleanup functionality\\n   338→- `session_state.go` - Package-level session state functions (`LoadSessionState`, `SaveSessionState`, `ListSessionStates`, `FindMostRecentSession`)\\n   339→- `auto_commit.go` - Auto-commit strategy implementation\\n   340→- `hooks.go` - Git hook installation\\n   341→\\n   342→#### Checkpoint Package (`cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/`)\\n   343→- `checkpoint.go` - Data types (`Checkpoint`, `TemporaryCheckpoint`, `CommittedCheckpoint`)\\n   344→- `store.go` - `GitStore` struct wrapping git repository\\n   345→- `temporary.go` - Shadow branch operations (`WriteTemporary`, `ReadTemporary`, `ListTemporary`)\\n   346→- `committed.go` - Metadata branch operations (`WriteCommitted`, `ReadCommitted`, `ListCommitted`)\\n   347→\\n   348→#### Session Package (`cmd/entire/cli/session/`)\\n   349→- `session.go` - Session data types and interfaces\\n   350→- `state.go` - `StateStore` for managing `.git/entire-sessions/` files\\n   351→- `phase.go` - Session phase state machine (phases, events, transitions, actions)\\n   352→\\n   353→#### Session Phase State Machine\\n   354→\\n   355→Sessions track their lifecycle through phases managed by a state machine in `session/phase.go`:\\n   356→\\n   357→**Phases:** `ACTIVE`, `IDLE`, `ENDED`\\n   358→\\n   359→**Events:**\\n   360→- `TurnStart` - Agent begins a turn (UserPromptSubmit hook)\\n   361→- `TurnEnd` - Agent finishes a turn (Stop hook)\\n   362→- `GitCommit` - A git commit was made (PostCommit hook)\\n   363→- `SessionStart` - New session started\\n   364→- `SessionStop` - Session explicitly stopped\\n   365→\\n   366→**Key transitions:**\\n   367→- `IDLE + TurnStart → ACTIVE` - Agent starts working\\n   368→- `ACTIVE + TurnEnd → IDLE` - Agent finishes turn\\n   369→- `ACTIVE + GitCommit → ACTIVE` - User commits while agent is working (condense immediately)\\n   370→- `IDLE + GitCommit → IDLE` - User commits between turns (condense immediately)\\n   371→- `ENDED + GitCommit → ENDED` - Post-session commit (condense if files touched)\\n   372→\\n   373→The state machine emits **actions** (e.g., `ActionCondense`, `ActionUpdateLastInteraction`) that hook handlers dispatch to strategy-specific implementations.\\n   374→\\n   375→#### Metadata Structure\\n   376→\\n   377→**Shadow Strategy** - Shadow branches (`entire/<commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>`):\\n   378→```\\n   379→.entire/metadata/<session-id>/\\n   380→├── full.jsonl               # Session transcript\\n   381→├── prompt.txt               # User prompts\\n   382→├── context.md               # Generated context\\n   383→└── tasks/<tool-use-id>/     # Task checkpoints\\n   384→    ├── checkpoint.json      # UUID mapping for rewind\\n   385→    └── agent-<id>.jsonl     # Subagent transcript\\n   386→```\\n   387→\\n   388→**Both Strategies** - Metadata branch (`entire/checkpoints/v1`) - sharded checkpoint format:\\n   389→```\\n   390→<checkpoint-id[:2]>/<checkpoint-id[2:]>/\\n   391→├── metadata.json            # CheckpointSummary (aggregated stats)\\n   392→├── 0/                       # First session (0-based indexing)\\n   393→│   ├── metadata.json        # Session-specific metadata\\n   394→│   ├── full.jsonl           # Session transcript\\n   395→│   ├── prompt.txt           # User prompts\\n   396→│   ├── context.md           # Generated context\\n   397→│   ├── content_hash.txt     # SHA256 of transcript\\n   398→│   └── tasks/<tool-use-id>/ # Task checkpoints (if applicable)\\n   399→│       ├── checkpoint.json  # UUID mapping\\n   400→│       └── agent-<id>.jsonl # Subagent transcript\\n   401→├── 1/                       # Second session (if multiple sessions)\\n   402→│   ├── metadata.json\\n   403→│   ├── full.jsonl\\n   404→│   └── ...\\n   405→└── ...\\n   406→```\\n   407→\\n   408→**Multi-session metadata.json format:**\\n   409→```json\\n   410→{\\n   411→  \\\"checkpoint_id\\\": \\\"abc123def456\\\",\\n   412→  \\\"session_id\\\": \\\"2026-01-13-uuid\\\",      // Current/latest session\\n   413→  \\\"session_ids\\\": [\\\"2026-01-13-uuid1\\\", \\\"2026-01-13-uuid2\\\"],  // All sessions\\n   414→  \\\"session_count\\\": 2,                    // Number of sessions in this checkpoint\\n   415→  \\\"strategy\\\": \\\"manual-commit\\\",\\n   416→  \\\"created_at\\\": \\\"2026-01-13T12:00:00Z\\\",\\n   417→  \\\"files_touched\\\": [\\\"file1.txt\\\", \\\"file2.txt\\\"]  // Merged from all sessions\\n   418→}\\n   419→```\\n   420→\\n   421→When multiple sessions are condensed to the same checkpoint (same base commit):\\n   422→- Sessions are stored in numbered subfolders using 0-based indexing (`0/`, `1/`, `2/`, etc.)\\n   423→- Latest session is always in the highest-numbered folder\\n   424→- `session_ids` array tracks all sessions, `session_count` increments\\n   425→\\n   426→**Session State** (filesystem, `.git/entire-sessions/`):\\n   427→```\\n   428→<session-id>.json            # Active session state (base_commit, checkpoint_count, etc.)\\n   429→```\\n   430→\\n   431→#### Checkpoint ID Linking\\n   432→\\n   433→Both strategies use a **12-hex-char random checkpoint ID** (e.g., `a3b2c4d5e6f7`) as the stable identifier linking user commits to metadata.\\n   434→\\n   435→**How checkpoint IDs work:**\\n   436→\\n   437→1. **Generated once per checkpoint**: Either when saving (auto-commit) or when condensing (manual-commit)\\n   438→\\n   439→2. **Added to user commits** via `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer:\\n   440→   - **Auto-commit**: Added programmatically when creating the commit\\n   441→   - **Manual-commit**: Added via `prepare-commit-msg` hook (user can remove it before committing)\\n   442→\\n   443→3. **Used for directory sharding** on `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch:\\n   444→   - Path format: `<id[:2]>/<id[2:]>/`\\n   445→   - Example: `a3b2c4d5e6f7` → `a3/b2c4d5e6f7/`\\n   446→   - Creates 256 shards to avoid directory bloat\\n   447→\\n   448→4. **Appears in commit subject** on `entire/checkpoints/v1` commits:\\n   449→   - Format: `Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7`\\n   450→   - Makes `git log entire/checkpoints/v1` readable and searchable\\n   451→\\n   452→**Bidirectional linking:**\\n   453→\\n   454→```\\n   455→User commit → Metadata:\\n   456→  Extract \\\"Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\" trailer\\n   457→  → Read a3/b2c4d5e6f7/ directory from entire/checkpoints/v1 tree at HEAD\\n   458→\\n   459→Metadata → User commits:\\n   460→  Given checkpoint ID a3b2c4d5e6f7\\n   461→  → Search user branch history for commits with \\\"Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\" trailer\\n   462→```\\n   463→\\n   464→Note: Commit subjects on `entire/checkpoints/v1` (e.g., `Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7`) are\\n   465→for human readability in `git log` only. The CLI always reads from the tree at HEAD.\\n   466→\\n   467→**Example:**\\n   468→```\\n   469→User's commit (on main branch):\\n   470→  \\\"Implement login feature\\n   471→\\n   472→  Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\"\\n   473→       ↓ ↑\\n   474→       Linked via checkpoint ID\\n   475→       ↓ ↑\\n   476→entire/checkpoints/v1 commit:\\n   477→  Subject: \\\"Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\"\\n   478→\\n   479→  Tree: a3/b2c4d5e6f7/\\n   480→    ├── metadata.json (checkpoint_id: \\\"a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\")\\n   481→    ├── full.jsonl (session transcript)\\n   482→    ├── prompt.txt\\n   483→    └── context.md\\n   484→```\\n   485→\\n   486→#### Commit Trailers\\n   487→\\n   488→**On user's active branch commits (both strategies):**\\n   489→- `Entire-Checkpoint: <checkpoint-id>` - 12-hex-char ID linking to metadata on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   490→  - Auto-commit: Always added when creating commits\\n   491→  - Manual-commit: Added by hook; user can remove to skip linking\\n   492→\\n   493→**On shadow branch commits (`entire/<commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>`) - manual-commit only:**\\n   494→- `Entire-Session: <session-id>` - Session identifier\\n   495→- `Entire-Metadata: <path>` - Path to metadata directory within the tree\\n   496→- `Entire-Task-Metadata: <path>` - Path to task metadata directory (for task checkpoints)\\n   497→- `Entire-Strategy: manual-commit` - Strategy that created the commit\\n   498→\\n   499→**On metadata branch commits (`entire/checkpoints/v1`) - both strategies:**\\n   500→\\n   501→Commit subject: `Checkpoint: <checkpoint-id>` (or custom subject for task checkpoints)\\n   502→\\n   503→Trailers:\\n   504→- `Entire-Session: <session-id>` - Session identifier\\n   505→- `Entire-Strategy: <strategy>` - Strategy name (manual-commit or auto-commit)\\n   506→- `Entire-Agent: <agent-name>` - Agent name (optional, e.g., \\\"Claude Code\\\")\\n   507→- `Ephemeral-branch: <branch>` - Shadow branch name (optional, manual-commit only)\\n   508→- `Entire-Metadata-Task: <path>` - Task metadata path (optional, for task checkpoints)\\n   509→\\n   510→**Note:** Both strategies keep active branch history **clean** - the only addition to user commits is the single `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer. Manual-commit never creates commits on the active branch (user creates them manually). Auto-commit creates commits but only adds the checkpoint trailer. All detailed session data (transcripts, prompts, context) is stored on the `entire/checkpoints/v1` orphan branch or shadow branches.\\n   511→\\n   512→#### Multi-Session Behavior\\n   513→\\n   514→**Concurrent Sessions:**\\n   515→- When a second session starts in the same directory while another has uncommitted checkpoints, a warning is shown\\n   516→- Both sessions can proceed - their checkpoints interleave on the same shadow branch\\n   517→- Each session's `RewindPoint` includes `SessionID` and `SessionPrompt` to help identify which checkpoint belongs to which session\\n   518→- On commit, all sessions are condensed together with archived sessions in numbered subfolders\\n   519→- Note: Different git worktrees have separate shadow branches (worktree-specific naming), so concurrent sessions in different worktrees do not conflict\\n   520→\\n   521→**Orphaned Shadow Branches:**\\n   522→- A shadow branch is \\\"orphaned\\\" if it exists but has no corresponding session state file\\n   523→- This can happen if the state file is manually deleted or lost\\n   524→- When a new session starts with an orphaned branch, the branch is automatically reset\\n   525→- If the existing session DOES have a state file (concurrent session in same directory), a `SessionIDConflictError` is returned\\n   526→\\n   527→**Shadow Branch Migration (Pull/Rebase):**\\n   528→- If user does stash → pull → apply (or rebase), HEAD changes but work isn't committed\\n   529→- The shadow branch would be orphaned at the old commit\\n   530→- Detection: base commit changed AND old shadow branch still exists (would be deleted if user committed)\\n   531→- Action: shadow branch is renamed from `entire/<old-hash>-<worktreeHash>` to `entire/<new-hash>-<worktreeHash>`\\n   532→- Session continues seamlessly with checkpoints preserved\\n   533→\\n   534→#### When Modifying Strategies\\n   535→- All strategies must implement the full `Strategy` interface\\n   536→- Register new strategies in `init()` using `Register()`\\n   537→- Test with `mise run test` - strategy tests are in `*_test.go` files\\n   538→- **Update this CLAUDE.md** when adding or modifying strategies to keep documentation current\\n   539→\\n   540→# Important Notes\\n   541→\\n   542→- **Before committing:** Follow the \\\"Before Every Commit (REQUIRED)\\\" checklist above - CI will fail without it\\n   543→- Integration tests: run `mise run test:integration` when changing integration test code\\n   544→- When adding new features, ensure they are well-tested and documented.\\n   545→- Always check for code duplication and refactor as needed.\\n   546→\\n   547→## Go Code Style\\n   548→- Write lint-compliant Go code on the first attempt. Before outputting Go code, mentally verify it passes `golangci-lint` (or your specific linter).\\n   549→- Follow standard Go idioms: proper error handling, no unused variables/imports, correct formatting (gofmt), meaningful names.\\n   550→- Handle all errors explicitly—don't leave them unchecked.\\n   551→- Reference `.golangci.yml` for enabled linters before writing Go code.\\n   552→\\n   553→## Accessibility\\n   554→\\n   555→The CLI supports an accessibility mode for users who rely on screen readers. This mode uses simpler text prompts instead of interactive TUI elements.\\n   556→\\n   557→### Environment Variable\\n   558→- `ACCESSIBLE=1` (or any non-empty value) enables accessibility mode\\n   559→- Users can set this in their shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`) for persistent use\\n   560→\\n   561→### Implementation Guidelines\\n   562→\\n   563→When adding new interactive forms or prompts using `huh`:\\n   564→\\n   565→**In the `cli` package:**\\n   566→Use `NewAccessibleForm()` instead of `huh.NewForm()`:\\n   567→```go\\n   568→// Good - respects ACCESSIBLE env var\\n   569→form := NewAccessibleForm(\\n   570→    huh.NewGroup(\\n   571→        huh.NewSelect[string]().\\n   572→            Title(\\\"Choose an option\\\").\\n   573→            Options(...).\\n   574→            Value(&choice),\\n   575→    ),\\n   576→)\\n   577→\\n   578→// Bad - ignores accessibility setting\\n   579→form := huh.NewForm(...)\\n   580→```\\n   581→\\n   582→**In the `strategy` package:**\\n   583→Use the `isAccessibleMode()` helper. Note that `WithAccessible()` is only available on forms, not individual fields, so wrap confirmations in a form:\\n   584→```go\\n   585→form := huh.NewForm(\\n   586→    huh.NewGroup(\\n   587→        huh.NewConfirm().\\n   588→            Title(\\\"Confirm action?\\\").\\n   589→            Value(&confirmed),\\n   590→    ),\\n   591→)\\n   592→if isAccessibleMode() {\\n   593→    form = form.WithAccessible(true)\\n   594→}\\n   595→if err := form.Run(); err != nil { ... }\\n   596→```\\n   597→\\n   598→### Key Points\\n   599→- Always use the accessibility helpers for any `huh` forms/prompts\\n   600→- Test new interactive features with `ACCESSIBLE=1` to ensure they work\\n   601→- The accessible mode is documented in `--help` output\\n   602→\"}]},\"uuid\":\"c0e48fb0-93ec-4d06-b508-a5e70b0b4d50\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-24T12:19:59.125Z\",\"toolUseResult\":{\"type\":\"text\",\"file\":{\"filePath\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments/CLAUDE.md\",\"content\":\"# Entire - CLI \\n\\nThis repo contains the CLI for Entire.\\n\\n## Architecture\\n\\n- CLI build with github.com/spf13/cobra and github.com/charmbracelet/huh \\n\\n## Key Directories\\n\\n### Commands (`cmd/`)\\n- `entire/`: Main CLI entry point\\n- `entire/cli`: CLI utilities and helpers\\n- `entire/cli/commands`: actual command implementations\\n- `entire/cli/agent`: agent implementations (Claude Code, Gemini CLI, OpenCode) - see [Agent Integration Checklist](docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md)\\n- `entire/cli/strategy`: strategy implementations - see section below\\n- `entire/cli/checkpoint`: checkpoint storage abstractions (temporary and committed)\\n- `entire/cli/session`: session state management\\n- `entire/cli/integration_test`: integration tests (simulated hooks)\\n- `entire/cli/e2e_test`: E2E tests with real agent calls (see E2E Tests section)\\n\\n## Tech Stack\\n\\n- Language: Go 1.25.x\\n- Build tool: mise, go modules\\n- Linting: golangci-lint\\n\\n## Development\\n\\n### Running Tests\\n```bash\\nmise run test\\n```\\n\\n### Running Integration Tests\\n```bash\\nmise run test:integration\\n```\\n\\n### Running All Tests (CI)\\n```bash\\nmise run test:ci\\n```\\n\\nIntegration tests use the `//go:build integration` build tag and are located in `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/`.\\n\\n### Running E2E Tests (Only When Explicitly Requested)\\n\\n**IMPORTANT: Do NOT run E2E tests proactively.** E2E tests make real API calls through AI agents, which consume tokens and cost money. Only run them when the user explicitly asks for E2E testing.\\n\\n```bash\\n# Requires Claude Code to be installed and authenticated\\nE2E_AGENT=claude-code go test -tags=e2e ./cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/...\\n\\n# Run a specific test\\nE2E_AGENT=claude-code go test -tags=e2e -run TestE2E_BasicWorkflow ./cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/...\\n```\\n\\nE2E tests:\\n- Use the `//go:build e2e` build tag\\n- Located in `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/`\\n- Test real agent interactions (Claude Code creating files, committing, etc.)\\n- Validate checkpoint scenarios documented in `docs/architecture/checkpoint-scenarios.md`\\n- Support multiple agents via `E2E_AGENT` env var (`claude-code`, `gemini`, `opencode`)\\n\\n**Environment variables:**\\n- `E2E_AGENT` - Agent to test with (default: `claude-code`)\\n- `E2E_CLAUDE_MODEL` - Claude model to use (default: `haiku` for cost efficiency)\\n- `E2E_TIMEOUT` - Timeout per prompt (default: `2m`)\\n\\n### Test Parallelization\\n\\n**Always use `t.Parallel()` in tests.** Every top-level test function and subtest should call `t.Parallel()` unless it modifies process-global state (e.g., `os.Chdir()`).\\n\\n```go\\nfunc TestFeature_Foo(t *testing.T) {\\n    t.Parallel()\\n    // ...\\n}\\n\\n// Integration tests: RunForAllStrategies handles t.Parallel() for subtests internally,\\n// but the top-level test still needs it\\nfunc TestFeature_Bar(t *testing.T) {\\n    t.Parallel()\\n    RunForAllStrategies(t, func(t *testing.T, env *TestEnv, strategyName string) {\\n        // ...\\n    })\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Exception:** Tests that modify process-global state cannot be parallelized. This includes `os.Chdir()`/`t.Chdir()` and `os.Setenv()`/`t.Setenv()` — Go's test framework will panic if these are used after `t.Parallel()`.\\n\\n### Linting and Formatting\\n```bash\\nmise run fmt && mise run lint\\n```\\n\\n### Before Every Commit (REQUIRED)\\n\\n**CI will fail if you skip these steps:**\\n\\n```bash\\nmise run fmt      # Format code (CI enforces gofmt)\\nmise run lint     # Lint check (CI enforces golangci-lint)\\nmise run test:ci  # Run all tests (unit + integration)\\n```\\n\\nOr combined: `mise run fmt && mise run lint && mise run test:ci`\\n\\n**Common CI failures from skipping this:**\\n- `gofmt` formatting differences → run `mise run fmt`\\n- Lint errors → run `mise run lint` and fix issues\\n- Test failures → run `mise run test` and fix\\n\\n### Code Duplication Prevention\\n\\nBefore implementing Go code, use `/go:discover-related` to find existing utilities and patterns that might be reusable.\\n\\n**Check for duplication:**\\n```bash\\nmise run dup           # Comprehensive check (threshold 50) with summary\\nmise run dup:staged    # Check only staged files\\nmise run lint          # Normal lint includes dupl at threshold 75 (new issues only)\\nmise run lint:full     # All issues at threshold 75\\n```\\n\\n**Tiered thresholds:**\\n- **75 tokens** (lint/CI) - Blocks on serious duplication (~20+ lines)\\n- **50 tokens** (dup) - Advisory, catches smaller patterns (~10+ lines)\\n\\nWhen duplication is found:\\n1. Check if a helper already exists in `common.go` or nearby utility files\\n2. If not, consider extracting the duplicated logic to a shared helper\\n3. If duplication is intentional (e.g., test setup), add a `//nolint:dupl` comment with explanation\\n\\n## Code Patterns\\n\\n### Error Handling\\n\\nThe CLI uses a specific pattern for error output to avoid duplication between Cobra and main.go.\\n\\n**How it works:**\\n- `root.go` sets `SilenceErrors: true` globally - Cobra never prints errors\\n- `main.go` prints errors to stderr, unless the error is a `SilentError`\\n- Commands return `NewSilentError(err)` when they've already printed a custom message\\n\\n**When to use `SilentError`:**\\nUse `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message instead of the raw error:\\n\\n```go\\n// In a command's RunE function:\\nif _, err := paths.RepoRoot(); err != nil {\\n    cmd.SilenceUsage = true  // Don't show usage for prerequisite errors\\n    fmt.Fprintln(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"Not a git repository. Please run 'entire enable' from within a git repository.\\\")\\n    return NewSilentError(errors.New(\\\"not a git repository\\\"))\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**When NOT to use `SilentError`:**\\nFor normal errors where the default error message is sufficient, just return the error directly. main.go will print it:\\n\\n```go\\n// Normal error - main.go will print \\\"unknown strategy: foo\\\"\\nreturn fmt.Errorf(\\\"unknown strategy: %s\\\", name)\\n```\\n\\n**Key files:**\\n- `errors.go` - Defines `SilentError` type and `NewSilentError()` constructor\\n- `root.go` - Sets `SilenceErrors: true` on root command\\n- `main.go` - Checks for `SilentError` before printing\\n\\n### Settings\\n\\nAll settings access should go through the `settings` package (`cmd/entire/cli/settings/`).\\n\\n**Why a separate package:**\\nThe `settings` package exists to avoid import cycles. The `cli` package imports `strategy`, so `strategy` cannot import `cli`. The `settings` package provides shared settings loading that both can use.\\n\\n**Usage:**\\n```go\\nimport \\\"github.com/entireio/cli/cmd/entire/cli/settings\\\"\\n\\n// Load full settings object\\ns, err := settings.Load()\\nif err != nil {\\n    // handle error\\n}\\nif s.Enabled {\\n    // ...\\n}\\n\\n// Or use convenience functions\\nif settings.IsSummarizeEnabled() {\\n    // ...\\n}\\n```\\n\\n**Do NOT:**\\n- Read `.entire/settings.json` or `.entire/settings.local.json` directly with `os.ReadFile`\\n- Duplicate settings parsing logic in other packages\\n- Create new settings helpers without adding them to the `settings` package\\n\\n**Key files:**\\n- `settings/settings.go` - `EntireSettings` struct, `Load()`, and helper methods\\n- `config.go` - Higher-level config functions that use settings (for `cli` package consumers)\\n\\n### Logging vs User Output\\n\\n- **Internal/debug logging**: Use `logging.Debug/Info/Warn/Error(ctx, msg, attrs...)` from `cmd/entire/cli/logging/`. Writes to `.entire/logs/`.\\n- **User-facing output**: Use `fmt.Fprint*(cmd.OutOrStdout(), ...)` or `cmd.ErrOrStderr()`.\\n\\nDon't use `fmt.Print*` for operational messages (checkpoint saves, hook invocations, strategy decisions) - those should use the `logging` package.\\n\\n**Privacy**: Don't log user content (prompts, file contents, commit messages). Log only operational metadata (IDs, counts, paths, durations).\\n\\n### Git Operations\\n\\nWe use github.com/go-git/go-git for most git operations, but with important exceptions:\\n\\n#### go-git v5 Bugs - Use CLI Instead\\n\\n**Do NOT use go-git v5 for `checkout` or `reset --hard` operations.**\\n\\ngo-git v5 has a bug where `worktree.Reset()` with `git.HardReset` and `worktree.Checkout()` incorrectly delete untracked directories even when they're listed in `.gitignore`. This would destroy `.entire/` and `.worktrees/` directories.\\n\\nUse the git CLI instead:\\n```go\\n// WRONG - go-git deletes ignored directories\\nworktree.Reset(&git.ResetOptions{\\n    Commit: hash,\\n    Mode:   git.HardReset,\\n})\\n\\n// CORRECT - use git CLI\\ncmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"reset\\\", \\\"--hard\\\", hash.String())\\n```\\n\\nSee `HardResetWithProtection()` in `common.go` and `CheckoutBranch()` in `git_operations.go` for examples.\\n\\nRegression tests in `hard_reset_test.go` verify this behavior - if go-git v6 fixes this issue, those tests can be used to validate switching back.\\n\\n#### Repo Root vs Current Working Directory\\n\\n**Always use repo root (not `os.Getwd()`) when working with git-relative paths.**\\n\\nGit commands like `git status` and `worktree.Status()` return paths relative to the **repository root**, not the current working directory. When Claude runs from a subdirectory (e.g., `/repo/frontend`), using `os.Getwd()` to construct absolute paths will produce incorrect results for files in sibling directories.\\n\\n```go\\n// WRONG - breaks when running from subdirectory\\ncwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // e.g., /repo/frontend\\nabsPath := filepath.Join(cwd, file)  // file=\\\"api/src/types.ts\\\" → /repo/frontend/api/src/types.ts (WRONG)\\n\\n// CORRECT - use repo root\\nrepoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()  // or strategy.GetWorktreePath()\\nabsPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, file)  // → /repo/api/src/types.ts (CORRECT)\\n```\\n\\nThis also affects path filtering. The `paths.ToRelativePath()` function rejects paths starting with `..`, so computing relative paths from cwd instead of repo root will filter out files in sibling directories:\\n\\n```go\\n// WRONG - filters out sibling directory files\\ncwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // /repo/frontend\\nrelPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", cwd)  // returns \\\"\\\" (filtered out as \\\"../api/file.ts\\\")\\n\\n// CORRECT - keeps all repo files\\nrepoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()\\nrelPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", repoRoot)  // returns \\\"api/file.ts\\\"\\n```\\n\\n**When to use `os.Getwd()`:** Only when you actually need the current directory (e.g., finding agent session directories that are cwd-relative).\\n\\n**When to use repo root:** Any time you're working with paths from git status, git diff, or any git-relative file list.\\n\\nTest case in `state_test.go`: `TestFilterAndNormalizePaths_SiblingDirectories` documents this bug pattern.\\n\\n### Session Strategies (`cmd/entire/cli/strategy/`)\\n\\nThe CLI uses a strategy pattern for managing session data and checkpoints. Each strategy implements the `Strategy` interface defined in `strategy.go`.\\n\\n#### Core Interface\\nAll strategies implement:\\n- `SaveStep()` - Save session step checkpoint (code + metadata)\\n- `SaveTaskStep()` - Save subagent task step checkpoint\\n- `GetRewindPoints()` / `Rewind()` - List and restore to checkpoints\\n- `GetSessionLog()` / `GetSessionInfo()` - Retrieve session data\\n- `ListSessions()` / `GetSession()` - Session discovery\\n\\n#### Available Strategies\\n\\n| Strategy | Main Branch | Metadata Storage | Use Case |\\n|----------|-------------|------------------|----------|\\n| **manual-commit** (default) | Unchanged (no commits) | `entire/<HEAD-hash>-<worktreeHash>` branches + `entire/checkpoints/v1` | Recommended for most workflows |\\n| **auto-commit** | Creates clean commits | Orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch | Teams that want code commits from sessions |\\n\\n#### Strategy Details\\n\\n**Manual-Commit Strategy** (`manual_commit*.go`) - Default\\n- **Does not modify** the active branch - no commits created on the working branch\\n- Creates shadow branch `entire/<HEAD-commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>` per base commit + worktree\\n- **Worktree-specific branches** - each git worktree gets its own shadow branch namespace, preventing conflicts\\n- **Supports multiple concurrent sessions** - checkpoints from different sessions in the same directory interleave on the same shadow branch\\n- Session logs are condensed to permanent `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch on user commits\\n- Builds git trees in-memory using go-git plumbing APIs\\n- Rewind restores files from shadow branch commit tree (does not use `git reset`)\\n- **Location-independent transcript resolution** - transcript paths are always computed dynamically from the current repo location (via `agent.GetSessionDir` + `agent.ResolveSessionFile`), never stored in checkpoint metadata. This ensures restore/rewind works after repo relocation or across machines.\\n- Tracks session state in `.git/entire-sessions/` (shared across worktrees)\\n- **Shadow branch migration** - if user does stash/pull/rebase (HEAD changes without commit), shadow branch is automatically moved to new base commit\\n- **Orphaned branch cleanup** - if a shadow branch exists without a corresponding session state file, it is automatically reset when a new session starts\\n- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n- `AllowsMainBranch() = true` - safe to use on main/master since it never modifies commit history\\n\\n**Auto-Commit Strategy** (`auto_commit.go`)\\n- Code commits to active branch with **clean history** (commits have `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer only)\\n- Metadata stored on orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch at sharded paths: `<id[:2]>/<id[2:]>/`\\n- Uses `checkpoint.WriteCommitted()` for metadata storage\\n- Checkpoint ID (12-hex-char) links code commits to metadata on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n- Full rewind allowed if commit is only on current branch (not in main); otherwise logs-only\\n- Rewind via `git reset --hard`\\n- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n- `AllowsMainBranch() = true` - creates commits on active branch, safe to use on main/master\\n\\n#### Key Files\\n\\n- `strategy.go` - Interface definition and context structs (`StepContext`, `TaskStepContext`, `RewindPoint`, etc.)\\n- `registry.go` - Strategy registration/discovery (factory pattern with `Get()`, `List()`, `Default()`)\\n- `common.go` - Shared helpers for metadata extraction, tree building, rewind validation, `ListCheckpoints()`\\n- `session.go` - Session/checkpoint data structures\\n- `push_common.go` - Shared PrePush logic for pushing `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch\\n- `manual_commit.go` - Manual-commit strategy main implementation\\n- `manual_commit_types.go` - Type definitions: `SessionState`, `CheckpointInfo`, `CondenseResult`\\n- `manual_commit_session.go` - Session state management (load/save/list session states)\\n- `manual_commit_condensation.go` - Condense logic for copying logs to `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n- `manual_commit_rewind.go` - Rewind implementation: file restoration from checkpoint trees\\n- `manual_commit_git.go` - Git operations: checkpoint commits, tree building\\n- `manual_commit_logs.go` - Session log retrieval and session listing\\n- `manual_commit_hooks.go` - Git hook handlers (prepare-commit-msg, post-commit, pre-push)\\n- `manual_commit_reset.go` - Shadow branch reset/cleanup functionality\\n- `session_state.go` - Package-level session state functions (`LoadSessionState`, `SaveSessionState`, `ListSessionStates`, `FindMostRecentSession`)\\n- `auto_commit.go` - Auto-commit strategy implementation\\n- `hooks.go` - Git hook installation\\n\\n#### Checkpoint Package (`cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/`)\\n- `checkpoint.go` - Data types (`Checkpoint`, `TemporaryCheckpoint`, `CommittedCheckpoint`)\\n- `store.go` - `GitStore` struct wrapping git repository\\n- `temporary.go` - Shadow branch operations (`WriteTemporary`, `ReadTemporary`, `ListTemporary`)\\n- `committed.go` - Metadata branch operations (`WriteCommitted`, `ReadCommitted`, `ListCommitted`)\\n\\n#### Session Package (`cmd/entire/cli/session/`)\\n- `session.go` - Session data types and interfaces\\n- `state.go` - `StateStore` for managing `.git/entire-sessions/` files\\n- `phase.go` - Session phase state machine (phases, events, transitions, actions)\\n\\n#### Session Phase State Machine\\n\\nSessions track their lifecycle through phases managed by a state machine in `session/phase.go`:\\n\\n**Phases:** `ACTIVE`, `IDLE`, `ENDED`\\n\\n**Events:**\\n- `TurnStart` - Agent begins a turn (UserPromptSubmit hook)\\n- `TurnEnd` - Agent finishes a turn (Stop hook)\\n- `GitCommit` - A git commit was made (PostCommit hook)\\n- `SessionStart` - New session started\\n- `SessionStop` - Session explicitly stopped\\n\\n**Key transitions:**\\n- `IDLE + TurnStart → ACTIVE` - Agent starts working\\n- `ACTIVE + TurnEnd → IDLE` - Agent finishes turn\\n- `ACTIVE + GitCommit → ACTIVE` - User commits while agent is working (condense immediately)\\n- `IDLE + GitCommit → IDLE` - User commits between turns (condense immediately)\\n- `ENDED + GitCommit → ENDED` - Post-session commit (condense if files touched)\\n\\nThe state machine emits **actions** (e.g., `ActionCondense`, `ActionUpdateLastInteraction`) that hook handlers dispatch to strategy-specific implementations.\\n\\n#### Metadata Structure\\n\\n**Shadow Strategy** - Shadow branches (`entire/<commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>`):\\n```\\n.entire/metadata/<session-id>/\\n├── full.jsonl               # Session transcript\\n├── prompt.txt               # User prompts\\n├── context.md               # Generated context\\n└── tasks/<tool-use-id>/     # Task checkpoints\\n    ├── checkpoint.json      # UUID mapping for rewind\\n    └── agent-<id>.jsonl     # Subagent transcript\\n```\\n\\n**Both Strategies** - Metadata branch (`entire/checkpoints/v1`) - sharded checkpoint format:\\n```\\n<checkpoint-id[:2]>/<checkpoint-id[2:]>/\\n├── metadata.json            # CheckpointSummary (aggregated stats)\\n├── 0/                       # First session (0-based indexing)\\n│   ├── metadata.json        # Session-specific metadata\\n│   ├── full.jsonl           # Session transcript\\n│   ├── prompt.txt           # User prompts\\n│   ├── context.md           # Generated context\\n│   ├── content_hash.txt     # SHA256 of transcript\\n│   └── tasks/<tool-use-id>/ # Task checkpoints (if applicable)\\n│       ├── checkpoint.json  # UUID mapping\\n│       └── agent-<id>.jsonl # Subagent transcript\\n├── 1/                       # Second session (if multiple sessions)\\n│   ├── metadata.json\\n│   ├── full.jsonl\\n│   └── ...\\n└── ...\\n```\\n\\n**Multi-session metadata.json format:**\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"checkpoint_id\\\": \\\"abc123def456\\\",\\n  \\\"session_id\\\": \\\"2026-01-13-uuid\\\",      // Current/latest session\\n  \\\"session_ids\\\": [\\\"2026-01-13-uuid1\\\", \\\"2026-01-13-uuid2\\\"],  // All sessions\\n  \\\"session_count\\\": 2,                    // Number of sessions in this checkpoint\\n  \\\"strategy\\\": \\\"manual-commit\\\",\\n  \\\"created_at\\\": \\\"2026-01-13T12:00:00Z\\\",\\n  \\\"files_touched\\\": [\\\"file1.txt\\\", \\\"file2.txt\\\"]  // Merged from all sessions\\n}\\n```\\n\\nWhen multiple sessions are condensed to the same checkpoint (same base commit):\\n- Sessions are stored in numbered subfolders using 0-based indexing (`0/`, `1/`, `2/`, etc.)\\n- Latest session is always in the highest-numbered folder\\n- `session_ids` array tracks all sessions, `session_count` increments\\n\\n**Session State** (filesystem, `.git/entire-sessions/`):\\n```\\n<session-id>.json            # Active session state (base_commit, checkpoint_count, etc.)\\n```\\n\\n#### Checkpoint ID Linking\\n\\nBoth strategies use a **12-hex-char random checkpoint ID** (e.g., `a3b2c4d5e6f7`) as the stable identifier linking user commits to metadata.\\n\\n**How checkpoint IDs work:**\\n\\n1. **Generated once per checkpoint**: Either when saving (auto-commit) or when condensing (manual-commit)\\n\\n2. **Added to user commits** via `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer:\\n   - **Auto-commit**: Added programmatically when creating the commit\\n   - **Manual-commit**: Added via `prepare-commit-msg` hook (user can remove it before committing)\\n\\n3. **Used for directory sharding** on `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch:\\n   - Path format: `<id[:2]>/<id[2:]>/`\\n   - Example: `a3b2c4d5e6f7` → `a3/b2c4d5e6f7/`\\n   - Creates 256 shards to avoid directory bloat\\n\\n4. **Appears in commit subject** on `entire/checkpoints/v1` commits:\\n   - Format: `Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7`\\n   - Makes `git log entire/checkpoints/v1` readable and searchable\\n\\n**Bidirectional linking:**\\n\\n```\\nUser commit → Metadata:\\n  Extract \\\"Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\" trailer\\n  → Read a3/b2c4d5e6f7/ directory from entire/checkpoints/v1 tree at HEAD\\n\\nMetadata → User commits:\\n  Given checkpoint ID a3b2c4d5e6f7\\n  → Search user branch history for commits with \\\"Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\" trailer\\n```\\n\\nNote: Commit subjects on `entire/checkpoints/v1` (e.g., `Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7`) are\\nfor human readability in `git log` only. The CLI always reads from the tree at HEAD.\\n\\n**Example:**\\n```\\nUser's commit (on main branch):\\n  \\\"Implement login feature\\n\\n  Entire-Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\"\\n       ↓ ↑\\n       Linked via checkpoint ID\\n       ↓ ↑\\nentire/checkpoints/v1 commit:\\n  Subject: \\\"Checkpoint: a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\"\\n\\n  Tree: a3/b2c4d5e6f7/\\n    ├── metadata.json (checkpoint_id: \\\"a3b2c4d5e6f7\\\")\\n    ├── full.jsonl (session transcript)\\n    ├── prompt.txt\\n    └── context.md\\n```\\n\\n#### Commit Trailers\\n\\n**On user's active branch commits (both strategies):**\\n- `Entire-Checkpoint: <checkpoint-id>` - 12-hex-char ID linking to metadata on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n  - Auto-commit: Always added when creating commits\\n  - Manual-commit: Added by hook; user can remove to skip linking\\n\\n**On shadow branch commits (`entire/<commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>`) - manual-commit only:**\\n- `Entire-Session: <session-id>` - Session identifier\\n- `Entire-Metadata: <path>` - Path to metadata directory within the tree\\n- `Entire-Task-Metadata: <path>` - Path to task metadata directory (for task checkpoints)\\n- `Entire-Strategy: manual-commit` - Strategy that created the commit\\n\\n**On metadata branch commits (`entire/checkpoints/v1`) - both strategies:**\\n\\nCommit subject: `Checkpoint: <checkpoint-id>` (or custom subject for task checkpoints)\\n\\nTrailers:\\n- `Entire-Session: <session-id>` - Session identifier\\n- `Entire-Strategy: <strategy>` - Strategy name (manual-commit or auto-commit)\\n- `Entire-Agent: <agent-name>` - Agent name (optional, e.g., \\\"Claude Code\\\")\\n- `Ephemeral-branch: <branch>` - Shadow branch name (optional, manual-commit only)\\n- `Entire-Metadata-Task: <path>` - Task metadata path (optional, for task checkpoints)\\n\\n**Note:** Both strategies keep active branch history **clean** - the only addition to user commits is the single `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer. Manual-commit never creates commits on the active branch (user creates them manually). Auto-commit creates commits but only adds the checkpoint trailer. All detailed session data (transcripts, prompts, context) is stored on the `entire/checkpoints/v1` orphan branch or shadow branches.\\n\\n#### Multi-Session Behavior\\n\\n**Concurrent Sessions:**\\n- When a second session starts in the same directory while another has uncommitted checkpoints, a warning is shown\\n- Both sessions can proceed - their checkpoints interleave on the same shadow branch\\n- Each session's `RewindPoint` includes `SessionID` and `SessionPrompt` to help identify which checkpoint belongs to which session\\n- On commit, all sessions are condensed together with archived sessions in numbered subfolders\\n- Note: Different git worktrees have separate shadow branches (worktree-specific naming), so concurrent sessions in different worktrees do not conflict\\n\\n**Orphaned Shadow Branches:**\\n- A shadow branch is \\\"orphaned\\\" if it exists but has no corresponding session state file\\n- This can happen if the state file is manually deleted or lost\\n- When a new session starts with an orphaned branch, the branch is automatically reset\\n- If the existing session DOES have a state file (concurrent session in same directory), a `SessionIDConflictError` is returned\\n\\n**Shadow Branch Migration (Pull/Rebase):**\\n- If user does stash → pull → apply (or rebase), HEAD changes but work isn't committed\\n- The shadow branch would be orphaned at the old commit\\n- Detection: base commit changed AND old shadow branch still exists (would be deleted if user committed)\\n- Action: shadow branch is renamed from `entire/<old-hash>-<worktreeHash>` to `entire/<new-hash>-<worktreeHash>`\\n- Session continues seamlessly with checkpoints preserved\\n\\n#### When Modifying Strategies\\n- All strategies must implement the full `Strategy` interface\\n- Register new strategies in `init()` using `Register()`\\n- Test with `mise run test` - strategy tests are in `*_test.go` files\\n- **Update this CLAUDE.md** when adding or modifying strategies to keep documentation current\\n\\n# Important Notes\\n\\n- **Before committing:** Follow the \\\"Before Every Commit (REQUIRED)\\\" checklist above - CI will fail without it\\n- Integration tests: run `mise run test:integration` when changing integration test code\\n- When adding new features, ensure they are well-tested and documented.\\n- Always check for code duplication and refactor as needed.\\n\\n## Go Code Style\\n- Write lint-compliant Go code on the first attempt. Before outputting Go code, mentally verify it passes `golangci-lint` (or your specific linter).\\n- Follow standard Go idioms: proper error handling, no unused variables/imports, correct formatting (gofmt), meaningful names.\\n- Handle all errors explicitly—don't leave them unchecked.\\n- Reference `.golangci.yml` for enabled linters before writing Go code.\\n\\n## Accessibility\\n\\nThe CLI supports an accessibility mode for users who rely on screen readers. This mode uses simpler text prompts instead of interactive TUI elements.\\n\\n### Environment Variable\\n- `ACCESSIBLE=1` (or any non-empty value) enables accessibility mode\\n- Users can set this in their shell profile (`.bashrc`, `.zshrc`) for persistent use\\n\\n### Implementation Guidelines\\n\\nWhen adding new interactive forms or prompts using `huh`:\\n\\n**In the `cli` package:**\\nUse `NewAccessibleForm()` instead of `huh.NewForm()`:\\n```go\\n// Good - respects ACCESSIBLE env var\\nform := NewAccessibleForm(\\n    huh.NewGroup(\\n        huh.NewSelect[string]().\\n            Title(\\\"Choose an option\\\").\\n            Options(...).\\n            Value(&choice),\\n    ),\\n)\\n\\n// Bad - ignores accessibility setting\\nform := huh.NewForm(...)\\n```\\n\\n**In the `strategy` package:**\\nUse the `isAccessibleMode()` helper. Note that `WithAccessible()` is only available on forms, not individual fields, so wrap confirmations in a form:\\n```go\\nform := huh.NewForm(\\n    huh.NewGroup(\\n        huh.NewConfirm().\\n            Title(\\\"Confirm action?\\\").\\n            Value(&confirmed),\\n    ),\\n)\\nif isAccessibleMode() {\\n    form = form.WithAccessible(true)\\n}\\nif err := form.Run(); err != nil { ... }\\n```\\n\\n### Key Points\\n- Always use the accessibility helpers for any `huh` forms/prompts\\n- Test new interactive features with `ACCESSIBLE=1` to ensure they work\\n- The accessible mode is documented in `--help` output\\n\",\"numLines\":602,\"startLine\":1,\"totalLines\":602}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"ac311c41-cc1a-4c91-a9a3-564797882c71\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"c0e48fb0-93ec-4d06-b508-a5e70b0b4d50\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments\",\"sessionId\":\"61c0a278-3171-4fc3-9c0d-e93853c2fe7f\",\"version\":\"2.1.47\",\"gitBranch\":\"docs/opencode-agent-documentation\",\"slug\":\"calm-munching-hinton\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_011J3zR24KScu5Kx4DA3YvFX\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_01SHcMeZUcUoUr3T9rq2qhm9\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments/GEMINI.md\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":210,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":45161,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":210},\"output_tokens\":1,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"}},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYStAC8qsZoAD41Vwu25r\",\"type\":\"assistant\",\"uuid\":\"9c53bbc0-4e4f-4b9d-b4fe-4d5a5337e9c8\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-24T12:19:59.328Z\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9c53bbc0-4e4f-4b9d-b4fe-4d5a5337e9c8\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments\",\"sessionId\":\"61c0a278-3171-4fc3-9c0d-e93853c2fe7f\",\"version\":\"2.1.47\",\"gitBranch\":\"docs/opencode-agent-documentation\",\"slug\":\"calm-munching-hinton\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"type\":\"hook_progress\",\"hookEvent\":\"PostToolUse\",\"hookName\":\"PostToolUse:Read\",\"command\":\"callback\"},\"parentToolUseID\":\"toolu_01SHcMeZUcUoUr3T9rq2qhm9\",\"toolUseID\":\"toolu_01SHcMeZUcUoUr3T9rq2qhm9\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-02-24T12:19:59.334Z\",\"uuid\":\"7395e9f8-0afd-4c5c-8f1f-d82028e37f14\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"9c53bbc0-4e4f-4b9d-b4fe-4d5a5337e9c8\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli_experiments\",\"sessionId\":\"61c0a278-3171-4fc3-9c0d-e93853c2fe7f\",\"version\":\"2.1.47\",\"gitBranch\":\"docs/opencode-agent-documentation\",\"slug\":\"calm-munching-hinton\",\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_01SHcMeZUcUoUr3T9rq2qhm9\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"     1→# Entire - CLI\\n     2→\\n     3→This repo contains the CLI for Entire.\\n     4→\\n     5→## Architecture\\n     6→\\n     7→- CLI build with github.com/spf13/cobra and github.com/charmbracelet/huh\\n     8→\\n     9→## Key Directories\\n    10→\\n    11→### Commands (`cmd/`)\\n    12→- `entire/`: Main CLI entry point\\n    13→- `entire/cli`: CLI utilities and helpers\\n    14→- `entire/cli/commands`: actual command implementations\\n    15→- `entire/cli/agent`: agent implementations (Claude Code, Gemini CLI, OpenCode) - see [Agent Integration Checklist](docs/architecture/agent-integration-checklist.md)\\n    16→- `entire/cli/strategy`: strategy implementations - see section below\\n    17→- `entire/cli/checkpoint`: checkpoint storage abstractions (temporary and committed)\\n    18→- `entire/cli/session`: session state management\\n    19→- `entire/cli/integration_test`: integration tests (simulated hooks)\\n    20→- `entire/cli/e2e_test`: E2E tests with real agent calls (see E2E Tests section)\\n    21→\\n    22→## Tech Stack\\n    23→\\n    24→- Language: Go 1.25.x\\n    25→- Build tool: mise, go modules\\n    26→- Linting: golangci-lint\\n    27→\\n    28→## Development\\n    29→\\n    30→### Running Tests\\n    31→```bash\\n    32→mise run test\\n    33→```\\n    34→\\n    35→### Running Integration Tests\\n    36→```bash\\n    37→mise run test:integration\\n    38→```\\n    39→\\n    40→### Running All Tests (CI)\\n    41→```bash\\n    42→mise run test:ci\\n    43→```\\n    44→\\n    45→Integration tests use the `//go:build integration` build tag and are located in `cmd/entire/cli/integration_test/`.\\n    46→\\n    47→### Running E2E Tests (Only When Explicitly Requested)\\n    48→\\n    49→**IMPORTANT: Do NOT run E2E tests proactively.** E2E tests make real API calls to AI agents, which consume tokens and cost money. Only run them when the user explicitly asks for E2E testing.\\n    50→\\n    51→```bash\\n    52→# Requires the agent to be installed and authenticated\\n    53→E2E_AGENT=claude-code go test -tags=e2e ./cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/...\\n    54→\\n    55→# Run a specific test\\n    56→E2E_AGENT=claude-code go test -tags=e2e -run TestE2E_BasicWorkflow ./cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/...\\n    57→```\\n    58→\\n    59→E2E tests:\\n    60→- Use the `//go:build e2e` build tag\\n    61→- Located in `cmd/entire/cli/e2e_test/`\\n    62→- Test real agent interactions (Claude Code, Gemini CLI, or OpenCode creating files, committing, etc.)\\n    63→- Validate checkpoint scenarios documented in `docs/architecture/checkpoint-scenarios.md`\\n    64→- Support multiple agents via `E2E_AGENT` env var (`claude-code`, `gemini`, `opencode`)\\n    65→\\n    66→**Environment variables:**\\n    67→- `E2E_AGENT` - Agent to test with (default: `claude-code`)\\n    68→- `E2E_CLAUDE_MODEL` - Claude model to use (default: `haiku` for cost efficiency)\\n    69→- `E2E_TIMEOUT` - Timeout per prompt (default: `2m`)\\n    70→\\n    71→### Linting\\n    72→```bash\\n    73→mise run lint\\n    74→```\\n    75→\\n    76→## Code Patterns\\n    77→\\n    78→### Error Handling\\n    79→\\n    80→The CLI uses a specific pattern for error output to avoid duplication between Cobra and main.go.\\n    81→\\n    82→**How it works:**\\n    83→- `root.go` sets `SilenceErrors: true` globally - Cobra never prints errors\\n    84→- `main.go` prints errors to stderr, unless the error is a `SilentError`\\n    85→- Commands return `NewSilentError(err)` when they've already printed a custom message\\n    86→\\n    87→**When to use `SilentError`:**\\n    88→Use `NewSilentError()` when you want to print a custom, user-friendly error message instead of the raw error:\\n    89→\\n    90→```go\\n    91→// In a command's RunE function:\\n    92→if _, err := paths.RepoRoot(); err != nil {\\n    93→    cmd.SilenceUsage = true  // Don't show usage for prerequisite errors\\n    94→    fmt.Fprintln(cmd.ErrOrStderr(), \\\"Not a git repository. Please run 'entire enable' from within a git repository.\\\")\\n    95→    return NewSilentError(errors.New(\\\"not a git repository\\\"))\\n    96→}\\n    97→```\\n    98→\\n    99→**When NOT to use `SilentError`:**\\n   100→For normal errors where the default error message is sufficient, just return the error directly. main.go will print it:\\n   101→\\n   102→```go\\n   103→// Normal error - main.go will print \\\"unknown strategy: foo\\\"\\n   104→return fmt.Errorf(\\\"unknown strategy: %s\\\", name)\\n   105→```\\n   106→\\n   107→**Key files:**\\n   108→- `errors.go` - Defines `SilentError` type and `NewSilentError()` constructor\\n   109→- `root.go` - Sets `SilenceErrors: true` on root command\\n   110→- `main.go` - Checks for `SilentError` before printing\\n   111→\\n   112→### Git Operations\\n   113→\\n   114→We use github.com/go-git/go-git for most git operations, but with important exceptions:\\n   115→\\n   116→#### go-git v5 Bugs - Use CLI Instead\\n   117→\\n   118→**Do NOT use go-git v5 for `checkout` or `reset --hard` operations.**\\n   119→\\n   120→go-git v5 has a bug where `worktree.Reset()` with `git.HardReset` and `worktree.Checkout()` incorrectly delete untracked directories even when they're listed in `.gitignore`. This would destroy `.entire/` and `.worktrees/` directories.\\n   121→\\n   122→Use the git CLI instead:\\n   123→```go\\n   124→// WRONG - go-git deletes ignored directories\\n   125→worktree.Reset(&git.ResetOptions{\\n   126→    Commit: hash,\\n   127→    Mode:   git.HardReset,\\n   128→})\\n   129→\\n   130→// CORRECT - use git CLI\\n   131→cmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"reset\\\", \\\"--hard\\\", hash.String())\\n   132→```\\n   133→\\n   134→See `HardResetWithProtection()` in `common.go` and `CheckoutBranch()` in `git_operations.go` for examples.\\n   135→\\n   136→Regression tests in `hard_reset_test.go` verify this behavior - if go-git v6 fixes this issue, those tests can be used to validate switching back.\\n   137→\\n   138→#### Repo Root vs Current Working Directory\\n   139→\\n   140→**Always use repo root (not `os.Getwd()`) when working with git-relative paths.**\\n   141→\\n   142→Git commands like `git status` and `worktree.Status()` return paths relative to the **repository root**, not the current working directory. When Gemini runs from a subdirectory (e.g., `/repo/frontend`), using `os.Getwd()` to construct absolute paths will produce incorrect results for files in sibling directories.\\n   143→\\n   144→```go\\n   145→// WRONG - breaks when running from subdirectory\\n   146→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // e.g., /repo/frontend\\n   147→absPath := filepath.Join(cwd, file)  // file=\\\"api/src/types.ts\\\" → /repo/frontend/api/src/types.ts (WRONG)\\n   148→\\n   149→// CORRECT - use repo root\\n   150→repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()  // or strategy.GetWorktreePath()\\n   151→absPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, file)  // → /repo/api/src/types.ts (CORRECT)\\n   152→```\\n   153→\\n   154→This also affects path filtering. The `paths.ToRelativePath()` function rejects paths starting with `..`, so computing relative paths from cwd instead of repo root will filter out files in sibling directories:\\n   155→\\n   156→```go\\n   157→// WRONG - filters out sibling directory files\\n   158→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // /repo/frontend\\n   159→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", cwd)  // returns \\\"\\\" (filtered out as \\\"../api/file.ts\\\")\\n   160→\\n   161→// CORRECT - keeps all repo files\\n   162→repoRoot, _ := paths.RepoRoot()\\n   163→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", repoRoot)  // returns \\\"api/file.ts\\\"\\n   164→```\\n   165→\\n   166→**When to use `os.Getwd()`:** Only when you actually need the current directory (e.g., finding agent session directories that are cwd-relative).\\n   167→\\n   168→**When to use repo root:** Any time you're working with paths from git status, git diff, or any git-relative file list.\\n   169→\\n   170→Test case in `state_test.go`: `TestFilterAndNormalizePaths_SiblingDirectories` documents this bug pattern.\\n   171→\\n   172→### Session Strategies (`cmd/entire/cli/strategy/`)\\n   173→\\n   174→The CLI uses a strategy pattern for managing session data and checkpoints. Each strategy implements the `Strategy` interface defined in `strategy.go`.\\n   175→\\n   176→#### Core Interface\\n   177→All strategies implement:\\n   178→- `SaveStep()` - Save session step checkpoint (code + metadata)\\n   179→- `SaveTaskStep()` - Save subagent task step checkpoint\\n   180→- `GetRewindPoints()` / `Rewind()` - List and restore to checkpoints\\n   181→- `GetSessionLog()` / `GetSessionInfo()` - Retrieve session data\\n   182→- `ListSessions()` / `GetSession()` - Session discovery\\n   183→\\n   184→#### Available Strategies\\n   185→\\n   186→| Strategy | Main Branch | Metadata Storage | Use Case |\\n   187→|----------|-------------|------------------|----------|\\n   188→| **manual-commit** (default) | Unchanged (no commits) | `entire/<HEAD-hash>` branches + `entire/checkpoints/v1` | Recommended for most workflows |\\n   189→| **auto-commit** | Creates clean commits | Orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch | Teams that want code commits from sessions |\\n   190→\\n   191→Legacy names `shadow` and `dual` are only recognized when reading settings or checkpoint metadata.\\n   192→\\n   193→#### Strategy Details\\n   194→\\n   195→**Manual-Commit Strategy** (`manual_commit*.go`) - Default\\n   196→- **Does not modify** the active branch - no commits created on the working branch\\n   197→- Creates shadow branch `entire/<HEAD-commit-hash>` per base commit for checkpoints\\n   198→- Session logs are condensed to permanent `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch on user commits\\n   199→- Builds git trees in-memory using go-git plumbing APIs\\n   200→- Rewind restores files from shadow branch commit tree (does not use `git reset`)\\n   201→- Tracks session state in `.git/entire-sessions/` (shared across worktrees)\\n   202→- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n   203→- `AllowsMainBranch() = true` - safe to use on main/master since it never modifies commit history\\n   204→\\n   205→**Auto-Commit Strategy** (`auto_commit.go`)\\n   206→- Code commits to active branch with **clean history** (commits have `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer only)\\n   207→- Metadata stored on orphan `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch at sharded paths: `<id[:2]>/<id[2:]>/`\\n   208→- Uses `checkpoint.WriteCommitted()` for metadata storage\\n   209→- Checkpoint ID (12-hex-char) links code commits to metadata on `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   210→- Full rewind allowed if commit is only on current branch (not in main); otherwise logs-only\\n   211→- Rewind via `git reset --hard`\\n   212→- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n   213→- `AllowsMainBranch() = false` - creates commits, so not recommended on main branch\\n   214→\\n   215→#### Key Files\\n   216→\\n   217→- `strategy.go` - Interface definition and context structs (`StepContext`, `TaskStepContext`, `RewindPoint`, etc.)\\n   218→- `registry.go` - Strategy registration/discovery (factory pattern with `Get()`, `List()`, `Default()`)\\n   219→- `common.go` - Shared helpers for metadata extraction, tree building, rewind validation, `ListCheckpoints()`\\n   220→- `session.go` - Session/checkpoint data structures\\n   221→- `push_common.go` - Shared PrePush logic for pushing `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch\\n   222→- `manual_commit.go` - Manual-commit strategy main implementation\\n   223→- `manual_commit_types.go` - Type definitions: `SessionState`, `CheckpointInfo`, `CondenseResult`\\n   224→- `manual_commit_session.go` - Session state management (load/save/list session states)\\n   225→- `manual_commit_condensation.go` - Condense logic for copying logs to `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   226→- `manual_commit_rewind.go` - Rewind implementation: file restoration from checkpoint trees\\n   227→- `manual_commit_git.go` - Git operations: checkpoint commits, tree building\\n   228→- `manual_commit_logs.go` - Session log retrieval and session listing\\n   229→- `manual_commit_hooks.go` - Git hook handlers (prepare-commit-msg, pre-push)\\n   230→- `manual_commit_reset.go` - Shadow branch reset/cleanup functionality\\n   231→- `auto_commit.go` - Auto-commit strategy 